          <p xml:id="Kali144-kilavi">ituvumatu atu. itaṟkum avvurai kūṟik koḷka.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en"></p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="Kali144">
              <l>naṉṉutāl  kāṇṭai niṉaiyā neṭituyirā</l>
              <l>veṉṉuṟṟāḷ kollō viḵtotti paṉmā</l>
              <l>ṇakutarun taṉṉāṇuk kaiviṭ ṭikutaruṅ</l>
              <l>kaṇṇīr tuṭaiyāk kaviḻntu nilaṉōkki</l>
              <l>yaṉṉa viṭumpai palaceytu taṉṉai</l>
              <l>viṉavuvārk kētila collik kaṉavupōṟ</l>
              <l>ṟeruḷu maruḷu mayaṅki varupavaḷ</l>
              <l>kūṟupa kēḷāmō ceṉṟu;</l>
              <l rend="space">ellānī, eṉṉaṇaṅ kuṟṟaṉai yārniṉ ṉituceytār</l>
              <l>niṉṉuṟṟa valla luraiyeṉa veṉṉai</l>
              <l>viṉavuvir teṟṟeṉak kēṇmi ṉoruvaṉ</l>
              <l>kuraṟkūntā leṉṉuṟṟa vevva niṉakkiyā</l>
              <l>ṉuraippaṉait taṅkiṟṟe ṉiṉṉuyi reṉṟu</l>
              <l>maruvūṭṭi māṟi yataṟkoṇ ṭeṉakku</l>
              <l>maruvaḻip paṭṭate ṉeñcu;</l>
              <l rend="space">eṅkun terintatu koḷvē ṉavaṉuḷvaḻi;</l>
              <l>poṅkiru munnī rakamellā nōkkiṉai</l>
              <l>tiṅkaḷuṭ ṭōṉṟi yirunta kuṟumuyā</l>
              <l>leṅkē ḷitaṉakat tuḷvaḻi kāṭṭīmō</l>
              <l>kāṭṭīyā yāyiṟ katanāy koḷuvuveṉ</l>
              <l>vēṭṭuva ruḷvaḻic ceppuve ṉāṭṭi</l>
              <l>matiyoṭu pāmpu maṭuppeṉ matitirinta</l>
              <l>veṉṉalla ṟīrā yeṉiṉ; </l>
              <l rend="space">eṉṟāṅkē, uṇṇiṉṟa vevva muraippa matiyoṭu</l>
              <l>veṇmaḻai yōṭip pukuti ciṟiteṉṉaik</l>
              <l>kaṇṇōṭi ṉāypōṟi nī;</l>
              <l rend="space">nīṭilait tāḻait tuvarmaṇaṟ kāṉalu</l>
              <l>ḷōṭuve ṉōṭi yoḷippeṉ poḻiṟoṟu</l>
              <l>nāṭuveṉ kaḷvaṉ karantirukkaṟ pālaṉko</l>
              <l>lāypū vaṭampi ṉalarkoṇ ṭutukkāṇeṅ</l>
              <l>kōtai puṉainta vaḻi;</l>
              <l rend="space">utukkāṇ, cāay malarkāṭṭic cālpilāṉ yāmāṭum</l>
              <l>pāvaikoṇ ṭōṭi yuḻi; </l>
              <l rend="space">utukkāṇ toyyil poṟitta vaḻi;</l>
              <l>utukkāṇ, taiyā ṟēṟeṉat tēṟṟi yaṟaṉillāṉ</l>
              <l>paiya muyaṅki yuḻi;</l>
              <l rend="space">aḷiyaveṉ ṉuḷḷat tuyavuttē rūrntu</l>
              <l>viḷiyānōy ceytiṟanta vaṉpi lavaṉait</l>
              <l>teḷiya vicumpiṉu ñālat takattum</l>
              <l>vaḷiyē yetirpōm palkatir ñāyiṟ</l>
              <l>ṟoḷiyuḷ vaḻiyellāñ ceṉṟu muṉipemmai</l>
              <l>yuṇmai nalaṉuṇ ṭoḷittāṉaik kāṭṭīmō</l>
              <l>kāṭṭāyēṉ, maṇṇaka mellā moruṅku cuṭuvēṉeṉ</l>
              <l>kaṇṇī raḻalāṟ ṟeḷittu;</l>
              <l rend="space">pēṇāṉ, tuṟantāṉai nāṭu miṭamviṭā yāyiṟ</l>
              <l>piṟaṅkiru munnīr veṟumaṇa lākap</l>
              <l>puṟaṅkāliṟ pōka viṟaippēṉ muyali</l>
              <l>laṟampuṇai yākalu muṇṭu;</l>
              <l rend="space">tuṟantāṉai, nāṭit tarukiṟpā yāyi ṉiṉakkoṉṟu</l>
              <l>pāṭuve ṉeṉṉō yuraittu; </l>
              <l rend="space">pulliya kēḷir puṇarum poḻutuṇarē</l>
              <l>ṉelliyā kellaiyeṉ ṟāṅkē pakaṉmuṉiva</l>
              <l>ṉelliyal kālai yirāmuṉivaṉ yāṉuṟṟa</l>
              <l>vallal kaḷaivā rilēṉ;</l>
              <l rend="space">ōokaṭalē, teṟṟeṉak kaṇṇuḷḷē tōṉṟa vimaiyeṭuttup</l>
              <l>paṟṟuve ṉeṉṟiyāṉ viḻikkuṅkāṉ maṟṟume</l>
              <l>ṉeñcattu ḷōṭi yoḷittāṅkē tuñcānōy</l>
              <l>ceyyu maṟaṉil lavaṉ;</l>
              <l rend="space">ōokaṭalē, ūrtalaik koṇṭu kaṉaluṅ kaṭuntīyu</l>
              <l>ṇīrpeytak kālē ciṉantaṇiyu maṟṟiḵtō</l>
              <l>vīramil kēḷva ṉuṟīiya kāmattī</l>
              <l>nīruṭ pukiṉuñ cuṭum; </l>
              <l rend="space">ōokaṭalē, eṟṟami lāṭṭiyeṉ ṉēmuṟṟā ḷeṉṟinnō</l>
              <l>yuṟṟaṟiyā tārō nakuka nayantāṅkē</l>
              <l>yiṟṟā vaṟiyiṉ muyaṅkaleṉ maṟṟeṉṉai</l>
              <l>yaṟṟattiṭ ṭāṟṟaṟuttāṉ mārpu;</l>
              <l rend="space">āṅku,</l>
              <l>kaṭaloṭu pulampuvōḷ kalaṅkañar tīrak</l>
              <l>keṭalaruṅ kātalar tuṉaitarap piṇinīṅki</l>
              <l>yaṟaṉaṟin toḻuku maṅka ṇāḷaṉait</l>
              <l>tiṟaṉilā reṭutta tīmoḻi yellā</l>
              <l>nallavai yuṭpaṭak keṭṭāṅ</l>
              <l>killā kiṉṟava ḷāynutaṟ pacappē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
              <l corresp="1">You with good forehead, see: thinking [and] sighing for a long time,</l>
              <l>what did she experience? One like this smiles</l>
              <l corresp="2f">many times. She lets go of her shame [and] sheds tears.</l>
              <l corresp="4">Without wiping the tears away, turning over she looks at the ground,</l>
              <l>does many sorrowful things like that, speaks </l>
              <l corresp="5f">strange [words] to those who ask her, like in a dream,</l>
              <l corresp="7">alternating between clarity and confusion, the one who comes [there],</l>
              <l corresp="8">won’t we go [and] here what she tells?</l>
              <l corresp="9">“Hey you, which torment did you experience? Who did this to you?</l>
              <l>Tell [us] about the unhappiness you undergo!”, so you may</l>
              <l corresp="10f">ask me. Listen clearly: one man,</l>
              <l>saying “you with curly tresses, my precious life will stay</l>
              <l corresp="12f">with me who tells you about the trouble I had”,</l>
              <l corresp="14">fed [me] with embraces, [and] taking [that as] something that won’t change,</l>
              <l corresp="15">my heart fell into desolation for [him] to embrace me.</l>
              <l>I will take to searching everywhere the way to him.</l>
              <l corresp="17">You who looked at all the inside of the churning dark three-water[ed sea],</l>
              <l corresp="18">little hare who sits, having appeared in the moon,</l>
              <l corresp="19">please show [me] the way to our kin inside of this.</l>
              <l corresp="20">If you don’t show [him], I will put an angry dog on you.</l>
              <l corresp="21">I will tell the way to the hunters. After chasing [you],</l>
              <l>I will swallow the snake along with the moon, </l>
              <l corresp="22f">if you don’t end my unhappiness that turns with the moon. (22f.)</l>
              <l>Having said so, when talking of the trouble that stays in the heart,</l>
              <l>running with the white clouds and the moon you would enter. A little</l>
              <l corresp="24-26">you would seem one who feels pity for me. </l>
              <l corresp="27">In the seashore grove with coral sand [and] long-leaved screw-pine trees</l>
              <l corresp="28">I run. Running, I hide in every grove.</l>
              <l corresp="29">I search the robber. Is it his fate to keep hiding?</l>
              <l>Taking blossoms from the hare-leaf with choice flowers, see there: </l>
              <l corresp="30f">the way our garland is made.</l>
              <l>Look there: we play with one without quality, showing sedges [and] blossoms,</l>
              <l corresp="32-33">when running with [our] doll.</l>
              <l corresp="34">See there, the way he impressed the sandal paste.</l>
              <l>See there: convincing [us] by saying “o woman, trust [me], he is without virtue,</l>
              <l corresp="35-36">when he gently embraced [me].</l>
              <l>Pitiable the feelings of distress of my heart. Him who is </l>
              <l corresp="37f">without love who passed by mounting [his] chariot [and] causing imperishable pain,</l>
              <l corresp="39-40a">clearly, o wind, in the sky and on earth,</l>
              <l corresp="41a-c">going with dislike all the ways in the light</l>
              <l corresp="40b-d">of the many-rayed sun that meets [you], </l>
              <l corresp="42">please show us the one who is in hiding after consuming [our] beauty for real.</l>
              <l corresp="43">If you don’t show [him], I will burn all the earth together,</l>
              <l corresp="44">making it clear with the fire of my tears. (44)</l>
              <l corresp="45">If you don’t let free the was on which [I] search for him who does not cherish, who has abandoned [me],</l>
              <l>o glistening dark three-water[ed sea], I will disperse [you]</l>
              <l corresp="46f">to go outside in a channel as different sand. If you make an effort,</l>
              <l corresp="48">there is also [the chance of] becoming a support in duty.</l>
              <l>If you can find [and] bring the one who has abandoned [me], </l>
              <l corresp="49-50">I will sing a song for you, talking of my pain.</l>
              <l>I don’t perceive a time when [I] will unite with my relatives who embrace [me].</l>
              <l>Thinking the day to be night thus I dislike the day.</l>
              <l>The night I dislike as the morning with the nature of night. </l>
              <l corresp="51-54">I have no one who removes the unhappiness I feel. </l>
              <l>Ah, sea, When he appears clearly before [my] eyes, in a moment I lift </l>
              <l>[and] seize [him], you may say. When I open [my] eyes again,</l>
              <l>he runs inside my heart, hides there [and] causes unsleeping pain,</l>
              <l corresp="55-58">the one without virtue. </l>
              <l>Ah, sea, at the time water is poured into a fierce fire</l>
              <l>that glows, taking over the village, [its] fury will calm down. As for this,</l>
              <l>the fire of passion caused by the kindred man without affection</l>
              <l corresp="59-62">will burn even if entered into water. </l>
              <l>Ah, sea, as for those who don’t know, not having felt this pain,</l>
              <l>saying “she who feels confusion is a woman without determination”, let them smile. </l>
              <l>If I had known that it is like this, longing thus, I would not have embraced</l>
              <l corresp="63-66">the chest of him who cut off [my] path, placing ruin on me.</l>
              <l>Thus,</l>
              <l corresp="68">so that the disturbing affliction ends of her who is lonely with love,</l>
              <l corresp="69">[her] sickness leaving when the lover difficult to lose makes haste,</l>
              <l corresp="70">the man there who acts in knowledge of [his] duty,</l>
              <l corresp="72">listening thus when they fall in the good assembly</l>
              <l corresp="71">to all the fiery words raised by those who have no issue with him,</l>
              <l corresp="73">it becomes naught, the pallor on her choice forehead.</l>
            </lg>
